The new framework needed to provide quantifiable measures of success, defined in a way which enabled Visit Wales to measure performance against a clear and communicable set of agreed criteria (targets) and that allowed forward planning and allocation of resources. Stakeholders were consulted on their opinions of what made a good KPI, and the task force developed a profile of an effective KPI – one which was actionable, meaningful, holistic, tailored, credible, and easily understood and relevant (Table 3
). A workshop session was then held with marketing and research teams, agencies, and other stakeholders involved in tourism marketing for Wales to discuss the task force’s findings. The assembled teams were asked to identify the major gaps in measuring marketing activity in order to generate a ‘shopping list’ of KPIs, which they did under the six key measures of value, sustainability, visit(ors), brand, campaign response, and campaign diagnostics (Table 4
). As with the senior DMO officers, these teams were concerned that the value of the internet needed to be assessed alongside and in conjunction with traditional marketing. Visitors are influenced by a variety of sources, not just the creative campaigns; for example, visitors are attracted by tactical offers, events, advocacy, or casual web search. The teams underlined the need for the new KPIs to reflect the requirements of reporting campaign effectiveness to WG and of generating insights of value to the campaign teams.

Seven new KPIs (destination awareness, total campaign awareness, claimed and known campaign response, emotional proximity, conviction to visit, conversion throughout the decision-making process, value per respondent) were finally agreed as a series of indicators that reflect the consumer journey from awareness to advocacy as expressed in the marketing funnel (Figure 3
). These new KPIs (described in Table 5
) have the advantage that at a strategic level they are each an individual, understandable measure of campaign and brand performance, but at the planning level, they fit together to paint a picture of the effect of marketing interventions on different groups throughout the consumer journey. For example, the new framework enables managers to answer questions such as ‘if a campaign has a high awareness score, what impact will this have on the destination awareness, response, emotional proximity, and critically the conviction to visit?’ The ability to measure these new KPIs over time now provides Visit Wales's marketing teams with more nuanced and relevant information to evaluate the total reach and impact of their campaigns.
